<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-116-207 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 175 103</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  July 1991 v38 n7 p28(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mass flow sensing improves leak detection.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hoffman, Jacques E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A fast and accurate assessment of final test results is needed inmanufacturing, along with a rapid identification of possibleproblems before rejects occur.andP;  Leak readings can be used toevaluate such attributes as assembly deficiencies, fit andfunction problems, and casting porosity.andP;  In addition, apotentially adverse change in a variable is possible to detectwith leak readings, making it possible to correct the problemwithout stopping production flow.andP;  Different types of leak testersare on the market.andP;  Many are too costly, with slow test cycles, orare too complex to be used for a production line environment.andO;Pressure decay testing using a pressure transducer is the leastexpensive, slowest method of leak detection, suitable for acceptor reject testing of low leak-volume ratio parts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Mass ProductionFlow RateProduction ControlTestingQuality ControlManufacturingProductivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Pressure decay - gauge pressure. (chart)Pressure decay - differential pressure. (chart)Mass flow. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>